Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #saucepan{} over medium high heat. While the pan heats up, drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #colander{}. Add the chickpeas to the saucepan along with the @chermoula spice mix{1}. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @water{}(boiling, see ingredients for amount) and @vegetable stock powder{1}. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a #lid{} on the saucepan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Chop the @tomato{2%medium} into 2cm chunks. Pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks, roughly chopped) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Zest, then halve the @lemon{1}. Cut the @halloumi{250%g} into 3 slices per person.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} over medium high heat. Once hot, lay in the halloumi. Cook the halloumi until golden brown, ~{2-3%mins} on each side.

Meanwhile, put the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} in a #small bowl{} and add half the mint and half the lemon zest. Season with @salt{to taste} and @ground black pepper{to taste}. Stir together and keep to one side.

When the halloumi is cooked, remove the frying pan from the heat and drizzle the @honey{15%g} over the halloumi. Stir the tomato, leftover lemon zest and mint into the bulgur wheat. Add salt, pepper and lemon juice to taste.

Share the bulgur between your plates and top with the halloumi slices. Finish with a dollop of herby yoghurt. Enjoy!

> A zesty blend of spices and herbs, chermoula is a Moroccan spice traditionally used to season fish and meat. But as you will see, chermoula also works brilliantly in vegetarian dishes like this one, complementing the sweetness of the honey and the freshness of the minty yoghurt dressing. Regardless of the weather outside, this recipe is guaranteed to take you to the warm, sunny climes of Northern Africa.